AGI - Sunday Catalonia will go to the urns> to choose the 135 Members of the new Regional Parliament, in a vote that represents an important test for the holding of the national executive and for the European elections in June. The three political parties in comparison in Catalonia - without perspective of agreements or alliances between them - are the same on which the socialist government of Pedro Sanchez stands.> If the next Catalan Parliament is expected to be fragmented, in Madrid the premier still governs thanks to the external support of the Catalan independent parties. The last polls for the Catalan elections - published last May 6 - give as winner the candidate of the Catalan Socialist Party (PSC), Salvador Illa>, former Minister of Health and friend of Sanchez. According to the results spread in the week, the socialists should be able to increase the consensus and obtain the simple majority, so without absolute majority they will not be able to govern alone. A scenario that recalls in part the votes of 2021, when, in the absence of majority, the philosopher-independent of the outgoing president Pere Aragones>, of the Republican Left of Catalonia (Erc, progressive), had managed to remain in power. Also this Sunday the Erc will be on the verge for the second place, but it will have to count with 'Togethers for Catalonia' (JxCat, independent center-right) of the independent leader Carles Puigdemont, > returned to the political scene after his convulse judicial events. At the vote the two are played the leadership of the independent front. Based on the polls, Puigdemont would be in a technical tie with the Aragones Erc or, according to some, could be in a slight advantage.
&nbsp;
However, the fight for the second position between Junts and Erc is very intense as both formations are immersed in a complex political scenario, where the strategy towards independence and the management of the health crisis are crucial issues. The leadership of Puigdemont in Junts and the Erc route under the Aragone's government are factors that influence this competition. In the race there is also the anti-capitalist Popular Unit Candidature (Cup), pro independence. For his part, the socialist candidate has assured that there will be no agreement with Puigdemont because the former president of Generalitat is "the block". His return to the political council of Catalonia is another of the incentives in these Catalan elections: the leader of JxCat continues to reiterate that on the independence of Catalonia the "work must be finished" >. On Sunday there is also the future of the same Puigdemont, which has already declared that if it does not win and will have no room for manoeuvre to articulate a parliamentary majority, it will not be the head of the opposition and will abandon political life.
&nbsp;
The uncertainty about possible pacts between parties was one of the main themes of the election campaign, also surclassifying what historically characterizes the eve of the appointment with the urns: the referendum on independence and positioning towards the government of Madrid. In fact the spectrum of a repetition of the elections aleggia nel aria and the Catalan socialist leader admitted the possibility of a "block" to his investiture at the presidency. In the debate, however, they took part in management issues, such as the drought that afflicts Catalonia, regional financing, infrastructure, immigration, education and health. On the last day of the election campaign, independent candidates took the opportunity to constantly attack socialist Illa. It was particularly enlivened after the president of the central government Sanchez contemplated possible resignation - never occurred - after the complaint to the wife Begona Gomez by the association "Manos limpias" - near the extreme right - for alleged corruption and traffic of influence.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Today in Catalonia will be a day of silence and reflection before the vote, in which at the moment the unknowns are more than certainties. In fact, with the tighter polls, the indecise represent the needle that can make the scales hang on either side. According to the Center for Opinion Studies, in recent days 35% of people had not yet decided > for which party will vote on 12 May. Moreover, 40% of the undecided hesitates between the PSC, Esquerra or Junts parties. After the Sunday elections, the Catalan Parliament will have to be reconstituted within 20 working days and the margin to form the new regional government is two months after the first investiture vote. However, whatever will be the result, the reflections on the governability of Spain will be evident for the double thread that binds Sanchez to Erc and JxCat. According to the newspaper 'El Pais', several sources of leadership of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party (Psoe) have denied that the candidate Illa can be "sacrified" to safeguard the stability of the national executive, underlining that the presidency of Catalonia remains the "priority". In fact a victory of the socialist candidate would be useful to counterbalance in part the territorial power of the People's Party (Pp), which governs in 12 regions out of 17, after the electoral success of last year. A socialist victory in Catalonia could also represent a significant boost for the Sanchez party in view of the European elections of 9 June.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

